{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17654761","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17654761"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:54:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:54:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18629"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18629","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18629"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11361"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113221"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11361","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11361"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18629"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95248"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10282"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26367"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26370"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113221","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113221"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESkeletal muscles can be classified according to their fascicle arrangement. Some muscles have fascicles that run parallel to the long axis of the muscle.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Compared with pennate muscles, which one of the following best describes a functional characteristic of parallel fascicle arrangement in skeletal muscle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Optimises force at longer lengths","Reduces energy consumption","Maximises range of movement","Increases muscle thickness","Generates maximum force per unit area"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaximises range of movement\u003C/strong\u003E is correct because parallel fascicles extend the full length of the muscle, allowing for greater shortening distances during contraction. This arrangement permits a wider range of motion compared to pennate muscles, though at the cost of reduced force production.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGenerates maximum force per unit area\u003C/strong\u003E - Pennate muscles generate more force per unit area due to more fibres packed into the same volume\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases muscle thickness\u003C/strong\u003E - Parallel arrangements typically result in longer, thinner muscles compared to pennate arrangements\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOptimises force at longer lengths\u003C/strong\u003E - Parallel muscles actually produce less force at longer lengths due to reduced overlap of actin and myosin filaments\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduces energy consumption\u003C/strong\u003E - Fascicle arrangement does not directly affect the metabolic efficiency of muscle contraction\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EExamples of muscles with parallel fascicles include the biceps brachii and sartorius, which require a large range of motion for their functions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Parallel fascicles in skeletal muscle are arranged longitudinally and extend the full length of the muscle.","Parallel fascicle arrangement maximises the distance over which a muscle can contract.","Parallel muscles have a greater range of motion but generate less force compared to pennate muscles."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95248"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18629"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95248","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95248"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-10T13:56:51+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-10T13:56:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11361"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113221"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4931"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Musculoskeletal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGrou